						               													<description>In Microchip, 2 to 5 players compete to create a structure that looks like a microchip with tiles depicting paths and connections.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Rules overview (please refer to rulebook):&amp;#10;&amp;#10;MATERIAL&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;bull;  5 boards&amp;#10;    &amp;bull;  Bag&amp;#10;    &amp;bull;  Box&amp;#10;    &amp;bull;  60 tiles in 5 colours, with the same distribution for each colour.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The initial setup depends on the number of players.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players draw tiles according to some simple constraint and place them on their boards so that:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;- The tile colours must match colours of the spaces they&amp;rsquo;re placed on. The square colours are a bit lighter for clarity.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;- The connections of the tiles must match with those of the adjacent tiles (if any).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;- Open connections towards the board edge are forbidden.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;They can test and re-arrange the tiles on their boards during play.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;After all the tiles have been drawn, the players will enjoy a few minutes to build their final microchips. There can be some tiles unused.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The player that created the most valuable microchip wins. The microchip value is the sum of the connections of each of its tiles. Unused tiles are worth minus 2 points.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;-description from designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
